ted Kingdom","Withington, Herefordshire, England":"Withington, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walwyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wal(d)wine</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, from elements meaning ‘power’ + ‘friend’.","from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Walweyn</i>, <i>Walwain</i>. The central French form of this name is <i>Gawain</i> (see   Gavin  ). This name is found in the medieval Arthurian romances and is traditionally explained as an adaptation of the Welsh name <i>Gwalchmei</i>, perhaps meaning ‘hawk of the plain’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gavin","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gábháin</b> or <b>Ó Gáibhín</b>, both of which are derived from diminutives of <i>gábhadh</i> ‘want’ or ‘danger’ (the second being the more likely meaning here).","Scottish and northern English: from the personal name <i>Gavin</i>, Scottish form of English <i>Gawain</i> and French   Gauvain  . The name was introduced into English from French versions of the Arthurian romances, where this name was borne by one of the knights of the Round Table, brother of Galahad and Mordred and a nephew of Arthur. It has been taken to be an adaptation of the Welsh name <i>Gwalchmei</i>, perhaps ‘hawk of the plain’.","Scottish: shortened form of   McGavin  , which is believed to be an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b> ‘son of the smith’."]}]},{"name":"Peryn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>(a)deryn</i> ‘blackbird’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"'Perinda'","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Czech (<b>Peřina</b>) and Slovak: nickname or metonymic occupational name from the vocabulary word <i>peřina</i> (Czech), <i>perina</i> (